Class PriorityDeque<E>

java.lang.Object
  java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      java.util.AbstractQueue<E>
          collections.PriorityQueue<E>
              collections.PriorityDeque<E>
Type Parameters:
E - the type of elements held in this deque
All Implemented Interfaces:
SortedCollection<E>, Serializable, Iterable<E>, Collection<E>, Deque<E>, Queue<E>
public final class PriorityDeque<E>
extends PriorityQueue<E>
implements Deque<E>

An unbounded priority Deque based on a modified red-black tree. The elements of this deque are ordered according to their natural ordering, or by an explicit Comparator provided at creation. Inserting null elements will fail cleanly and safely leaving this deque unmodified. Querying for null elements is allowed. Attempting to insert non-comparable elements will result in a ClassCastException . The addFirst(E), addLast(E), offerFirst(E), offerLast(E), and push(E) operations are not supported.

This deque is ordered from least to greatest with respect to the specified ordering. Elements with equal priority are ordered according to their insertion order.

The iterator() and descendingIterator() methods return fail-fast iterators which are guaranteed to traverse the elements of the deque in priority and reverse priority order, respectively. Attempts to modify the elements in this deque at any time after an iterator is created, in any way except through the iterator's own remove method, will result in a ConcurrentModificationException.

This deque is not thread-safe. If multiple threads modify this deque concurrently it must be synchronized externally, consider "wrapping" the deque using the Collections3.synchronizedDeque(Deque) method.

Implementation Note:This implementation uses a comparator (whether or not one is explicitly provided) to maintain priority order, and equals when testing for element equality. The ordering imposed by the comparator must be consistent with equals if this deque is to function correctly.

The underlying red-black tree provides the following worst case running time (where n is the size of this queue, and m is the size of the specified collection):

Note: This deque uses the same ordering rules as java.util.PriorityQueue. In comparison it provides identical functionality, faster overall running time and ordered traversals via its iterators.

create

public static <E> PriorityDeque<E> create(Iterable<? extends E> elements)
Creates a new PriorityDeque containing the elements of the specified Iterable. If the specified iterable is an instance of of SortedSet, java.util.PriorityQueue, or SortedCollection this deque will be ordered according to the same ordering. Otherwise, this priority deque will be ordered according to the natural ordering of its elements.

Parameters:
elements - the iterable whose elements are to be placed into the deque
Returns:
a new PriorityDeque containing the elements of the specified iterable
Throws:
ClassCastException - if elements of the specified iterable cannot be compared to one another according to the priority deque's ordering
NullPointerException - if any of the elements of the specified iterable or the iterable itself is null
